Question: Do you have any additional ideas, concerns, or feedback you would like to share to help ACME better serve the public?

Response ID: resp_1945
Response Text: From what I've seen, this entire endeavor has been badly handled from day one.  Apparently the initial activities were very secretive and not accessible, especially to the artists and groups who were targeted.  Two excuses given re: conflicts of interest and open meetings were clearly not legal and set off this project as an exercise of competitive and political power.  The announcement and the survey are extremely misleading regarding the issues that are actually driving this attempt to change existing programs.  Surveying who? - if you're asking the average citizen or even the avid audience member about these issues without disclosing what the basis of the overhaul is, and seeing the actual questions that are bland and so open-ended as to be useless, you're definitely setting the stage for winners and losers that you choose.  I did participate in the project that planned the existing funding for Thrive, Elevate, etc. - and it was inclusive, managed by outside consultants without a pre-determined agenda, and gave opportunities of a wide variety of artists, small groups, and major groups to be included in the development.  That's the opposite of the current endeavor; it really needs to be completely rejected and the city needs to start over with clear objectives and accessible communications that do not start with the "requested" changes to the programs while developing a rationale and process that gets you to those objectives.  That's backwards, and any consultant or business leader would recognize that game immediately.  Stop, apologize, and start over.

